The Telegraph - Calcutta : International

 London cabs in Pak

 IMTIAZ GUL 

 A London taxi cab: Karachi road trip

 Islamabad, June 16: Pakistan plans to import 300 of the renowned London taxi cabs to provide economical and reliable means of transportation to its people. 

 The central government, which has already allowed duty-free import of the cabs on a trial basis, says the service will be launched initially in Islamabad, Lahore and Karachi. 

 Equipped with the best of modern technology, such as satellite tracking, the cabs will arrive in Pakistan by the end of July, state minister for privatisation and investment Umar Ahmad Ghuman said in Islamabad today. 

 A Britain-based Pakistani company, Prime Transport Limited, will invest $1 billion to set up an assembly plant for the 2,400cc London taxis, also known as the Black Cab, at Gharo town in southern Sindh province. It will assemble 18,000 taxis annually. 

 In Britain, each taxi costs ?42,000, Ghuman said. 

 The decision to allow import of the taxicabs and to set up their assembly plant is aimed to provide people with a safe, economical and reliable taxi service, the state minister said. 

 He added that DaimlerChrysler has also shown interest in establishing an assembly plant near Sheikhupura city in Punjab province. 




